AuthzClientCryptoProvider.getBouncyCastleProvider() does not return a BouncyCastle provider as required by the CryptoProvider contract/Javadoc; it returns the provider of the default KeyStore type instead. Evidence (diff):
```java
@Override
public Provider getBouncyCastleProvider() {
    try {
        return KeyStore.getInstance(KeyStore.getDefaultType()).getProvider();
    } catch (KeyStoreException e) {
        throw new IllegalStateException(e);
    }
}
```
CryptoProvider Javadoc says it must return a BouncyCastle (FIPS or non-FIPS) Provider.

ASN1Decoder.readLength() performs an incorrect bounds check against the total input size (limit) rather than remaining bytes, and uses `>= limit`, which can reject valid encodings after some bytes have already been consumed. Evidence (diff):
```java
if (length >= limit) {
    throw new IOException("corrupted stream - out of bounds length found");
}
```
Here `limit` is initialized to `bytes.length` and does not account for already-read bytes (`count`).

ASN1Decoder.readSequence() mixes units when decrementing `length`: `length` is the SEQUENCE content length, but it subtracts `bytes.length` where `bytes` is the full TLV returned by readNext() (tag+len+value). This can cause premature termination or incorrect parsing. Evidence (diff):
```java
int length = readLength();
...
while (length > 0) {
    byte[] bytes = readNext();
    result.add(bytes);
    length = length - bytes.length;
}
```
And readNext():
```java
mark();
int tag = readTag();
readTagNumber(tag);
int length = readLength();
length += reset();
return read(length);
```
`reset()` adds back the header bytes, so `readNext()` returns TLV length, not just value length.

ASN1Decoder.readLength() returns -1 for indefinite-length encoding (0x80), but callers do not handle it; readNext() can compute a negative length and then call read(length), leading to NegativeArraySizeException. Evidence (diff):
```java
if (length == 0x80) {
    return -1;      // indefinite-length encoding
}
```
Caller readNext():
```java
int length = readLength();
length += reset();
return read(length);
```
If readLength() returns -1 and reset() returns 0, read(-1) will attempt `new byte[-1]`.

AuthzClientCryptoProvider.getEcdsaCryptoProvider().concatenatedRSToASN1DER() contains two no-op ASN1Encoder writes that are unused, indicating incorrect/leftover logic (dead code). Evidence (diff):
```java
ASN1Encoder.create().write(rBigInteger);
ASN1Encoder.create().write(sBigInteger);

return ASN1Encoder.create()
        .writeDerSeq(
                ASN1Encoder.create().write(rBigInteger),
                ASN1Encoder.create().write(sBigInteger))
        .toByteArray();
```
The first two encoder instances are discarded and do not contribute to the returned DER.

https://github.com/grafana/grafana/pull/:
SQL expressions feature toggle is broken and always disables SQL: pkg/expr/reader.go adds enableSqlExpressions() which always returns false regardless of the feature flag state:
```
func enableSqlExpressions(h *ExpressionQueryReader) bool {
  enabled := !h.features.IsEnabledGlobally(featuremgmt.FlagSqlExpressions)
  if enabled {
    return false
  }
  return false
}
```
ReadQuery() then rejects QueryTypeSQL whenever !enabled, so SQL queries can never be enabled.

MetricsMiddleware is statefully reused across decorated clients: NewMetricsMiddleware creates a single *MetricsMiddleware (imw) and, inside the returned middleware func, mutates imw.next = next and returns the same imw instance. If the middleware factory is used to wrap more than one client, the downstream 'next' can be overwritten, causing requests to be forwarded to the wrong client. Evidence (diff):
```
func NewMetricsMiddleware(...) plugins.ClientMiddleware {
  imw := newMetricsMiddleware(...)
  return plugins.ClientMiddlewareFunc(func(next plugins.Client) plugins.Client {
    imw.next = next
    return imw
  })
}
```

ContextualLoggerMiddleware can panic on nil requests: its methods dereference req.PluginContext without checking req for nil. Evidence (diff):
```
func (m *ContextualLoggerMiddleware) QueryData(ctx context.Context, req *backend.QueryDataRequest) (*backend.QueryDataResponse, error) {
  ctx = instrumentContext(ctx, endpointQueryData, req.PluginContext) // req may be nil
  return m.next.QueryData(ctx, req)
}
```
Same pattern in CallResource/CheckHealth/CollectMetrics.

