Email comparisons are case-sensitive in multiple places, causing real incorrect behavior: (a) attendee authorization can fail if casing differs between stored attendee email and `user.email`; (b) duplicate filtering can allow duplicates with different casing; (c) blacklist can be bypassed because blacklist entries are lowercased but `guest` is not. Evidence (packages/trpc/server/routers/viewer/bookings/addGuests.handler.ts):
```ts
const isAttendee = !!booking.attendees.find((attendee) => attendee.email === user.email);
...
const blacklistedGuestEmails = ...split(",").map((email) => email.toLowerCase());
...
const uniqueGuests = guests.filter(
  (guest) =>
    !booking.attendees.some((attendee) => guest === attendee.email) &&
    !blacklistedGuestEmails.includes(guest)
);
```

sendAddGuestsEmails references `AttendeeScheduledEmail` but it is not imported in packages/emails/email-manager.ts, which will cause a compile-time error. Evidence (packages/emails/email-manager.ts):
```ts
if (newGuests.includes(attendee.email)) {
  return sendEmail(() => new AttendeeScheduledEmail(calendarEvent, attendee));
} else {
  return sendEmail(() => new AttendeeAddGuestsEmail(calendarEvent, attendee));
}
```
No `import AttendeeScheduledEmail ...` exists in the shown diff for email-manager.ts.

sendAddGuestsEmails uses the wrong list when deciding which attendees are 'new': addGuestsHandler computes `uniqueGuests` (actually added) but calls `sendAddGuestsEmails(evt, guests)` with the original input, so emails can be misclassified/sent incorrectly when some inputs were filtered out (already attendees / blacklisted). Evidence (packages/trpc/server/routers/viewer/bookings/addGuests.handler.ts):
```ts
const uniqueGuests = guests.filter(...);
...
await sendAddGuestsEmails(evt, guests);
```

