GoogleCalendarService.updateEvent/deleteEvent: broken fallback calendar selection when externalCalendarId is falsy. In packages/app-store/googlecalendar/lib/CalendarService.ts the code does:

- updateEvent:
  const selectedCalendar = externalCalendarId ? externalCalendarId : event.destinationCalendar?.find((cal) => cal.externalId === externalCalendarId)?.externalId;

- deleteEvent:
  const calendarId = externalCalendarId ? externalCalendarId : event.destinationCalendar?.find((cal) => cal.externalId === externalCalendarId)?.externalId;

Because the else-branch only runs when externalCalendarId is falsy/undefined, the predicate compares cal.externalId === undefined and will almost always return undefined. This can pass an undefined calendarId to Google API calls (or fall back incorrectly), causing updates/deletes to fail or target the wrong calendar.

EventManager.create: runtime crash when destinationCalendar is empty/undefined. In packages/core/EventManager.ts:

const [mainHostDestinationCalendar] = evt.destinationCalendar ?? [];
if (evt.location === MeetLocationType && mainHostDestinationCalendar.integration !== "google_calendar") {
  evt["location"] = "integrations:daily";
}

If destinationCalendar is [] (common after this PR, e.g. webhook.e2e.ts changed destinationCalendar to []), mainHostDestinationCalendar is undefined and accessing .integration throws.

EventManager.updateAllCalendarEvents: can call updateEvent with an undefined credential. In packages/core/EventManager.ts, inside the loop over references:

if (reference.credentialId) {
